  "doc_id": "2452",
  "text": "Although increased temperatures are likely to alter scavenging community dynamics on land, effects of climate change presumably also will be widespread and detrimental to organisms in deep-sea ecosystems due to their inextricable link to surface productivity. For example, in marine ecosystems projected climate change models indicate that surface production of organic material could decline by more than 50%, drastically reducing the availability of resources to food-limited abyssal ecosystems [CITATION_1] . Such a dramatic decrease in food availability undoubtedly would constrain populations of benthic scavengers, potentially reducing biodiversity on the sea floor.",
